{
  "doc_id": "26615",
  "text": "Radiographic measurements, which are considered a standard measurement, have been used in several studies to assess the effectiveness of therapy or development of GHS over time. Generally, the X ray approach has been shown to be reliable [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and valid [CITATION_3] . Three different main methods measure GHS with the use of X rays: the anteroposterior view [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , the plane of the scapula method (at 30° to the coronal plane) [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , and the calculation of three-dimensional distances by two X rays (at 0° and at 45° or at 30° to the coronal plane) [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Splitting the radiographical data into categories [CITATION_11] has been shown not to be a reliable method [CITATION_12] . However, several problems, such as costs, exposure to radiation, or delayed feedback for therapeutic choices, make measurements difficult to put into practice in many clinical settings [CITATION_13] . Moreover, some radiographic methods require specialized equipment that is not widely available.",
